If it was your first time eating there, you knew you'd be finishing the entire bowl.

I've ordered Vesti's sandwich boxes for multiple events:  birthdays, school events, backyard parties, concert productions.  Fed 20-75 people, often needing food to be avail for long windows (4-6 hours)

Things that keep me coming back/set Vesti apart:
1) sandwiches keep VERY well.  Can sit out all day/don't get soggy/stale...great for feeding people over a prolonged period
2) sandwiches are cut in perfectly reasonable "grab a quick bite."  squares.  Not too big, not too small, constructed in a way that the sandwich doesn't fall apart on you.  Neatly made sandwiches that function well in one hand while using the other to type, hold your child, hold a drink
3) presentation is amazing.  Box opens to neatly cut squares surrounded by butcher paper...you want to eat one.  Remains inviting even after many of the sandwiches have been taken...it doesn't turn into a sad sandwich platter.
4) The vegetarian caprese & vegan sandwiches are great. I order a split box. Non-vegans love them too
5) The sandwiches don't "get cold or old."  Can be stored in the fridge, can be stored at room temp, can sit outside on a hot day.  I've kept them for a week in my fridge - they're great a week later.

I rank Vesti up against any catering / group feed scenario I've ever dealt with. Home run.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'I am a tour manager/event planner ordering food for 20-100 heads daily.

Japanese fusion in an electric, fun-inducing atmosphere it definitely lived up to hype!!
I will say the only negative was the “single treatment”; I get LA restaurants kind of frown on single dining yet to me it shouldn’t matter. The reservation system only allows for 2 people; I arrived told her I was just one she got very pushy wanting me to sit at the bar. I don’t want to sit at the bar; I’d like a regular table just like everyone else. She then asks me to step aside and seats everyone else in line then comes back to me literally sits me in front of the door. I just didn’t feel very welcome maybe it’s a local thing I don’t know.
For the food; it definitely lived up to the hype. I got the pork Coppa (perfectly cooked pork; on its own the fish sauce is little overwhelming yet with the hot mustard and cucumbers it’s a perfect bite). I ordered the negima skewers (chicken)-again excellent the sauce on the bottom-yum.
I ended my dinner with the strawberry milk soft serve complete with a shovel how fun!! Some great soft serve!!
Overall I’d highly recommend this spot; fun atmosphere, great tasting unique food you can’t go wrong.

We were told that the plates were small and the waitress recommended ordering 5-6 plates to share. We ordered 6, but to our surprise, the serving sizes were actually pretty big.

We ordered the Chefs salad, which was personally my favorite. Very flavorful dressing and a big pile of pecorino cheese, which I love. We also had the yellowtail sashimi, spicy tuna hand roll (comes with 4 seaweed squares for you to make your own) chicken wings (perfect crunch and sweetness), salmon aburri and the yakisoba (which we only had a bite of and took the rest to go because we were already full by the 3rd course.)

But no complaints here. The food was fantastic, we just know not to order so much next time, or to come here completely famished. The decor was cool and modern, music was really loud… it was difficult to have a conversation without having to repeat ourselves, but the ambiance was still cozy. Waitress was attentive and friendly, although I wish she would have cleared the food crumbs in between courses because our table got pretty messy.

All in all, we really enjoyed eating here, and it is definitely a nice addition to the neighborhood. The latter is one of my favorites.

This pizzeria has a half-open kitchen where you can watch them make the pizzas. The oven is typically pitfire-shaped but gas-driven, which makes for less flavor than a wood-burning pitfire.

We went there around 4 p.m. after a trip from La Brea and happened to catch the happy hour: $10 for one of most of their pizzas and $6 for a draft beer. The price was cheap, and the beer was very good. We had THREE PHILOSOPHERS and Figueroa Mountain Light Lager; both beers were good.

Regarding the food:

Boneless Wings
I had never had boneless wings before—interesting? The boneless wings were really tender and juicy, with a mild garlic ginger dipping sauce that balanced very well. I was curious about the texture of the boneless wings and guessed they weren’t real wings, but my friend Danny didn’t agree. We asked the waiter, and he told us they were chicken wings with the bones removed. Later on, I did some research and found that the culinary term "boneless wings" actually refers to chicken breasts. Anyway, the boneless wings were hot, crispy, and tender. I give them 9/10.

Margherita Pizza
Sadly, the most anticipated item was the worst. It was plain and boring—you couldn’t taste the tomato or the wheat, and it didn’t even have a sour flavor. We were all surprised that they could make a Margherita pizza so tasteless. A Margherita pizza is so easy to make with good cheese, good tomatoes, and good flour, but it seemed this pizza had none of those. Sorry, 0/10.

Honey Bear Pizza
This pizza was better than the Margherita one, but still not a good pizza. I'd rate it 5/10.

Little Gem Caesar Salad
Acceptable, but nothing special. The lettuce was fresh, but the cheese cubes were rubbery. Found this location when searching for breweries in the downtown area. Super glad I found this gem of a brewery a short walk from the bustling of downtown and even a shorter walk from Union station. The brewery is located in a less traffic area of L.A. which provides some what of a peaceful place to enjoy the dining experience with friends or family.

Bar food is quite good and pairs well with whatever beverage you choose. Our party ordered the cheeseburger, hotdog, fries, and chips with queso. All the food came out at the same time and was presented nicely. Taste was what you expect of delicious and flavorful greasy bar food. I did notice that there are healthy options such as salads.

The beer was great! Tried the IPA and the pilsners. Served cold! Foam is just right. The IPA citrus was satisfying on a warm day. I learned all beer is brewed here. During our visit I notice the fermentation tanks were being cleaned out by. It was a nice conversation point and we enjoyed the ambiance.

Plenty of seating indoors and outdoors but during peak hours there maybe standing room only. We arrived on a Saturday near 7p.m. and was lucky enough to find a party to share their table. Service was awesome. Staff like Andy were welcoming and suggested what beers to try. Can't say enough great things about this place. You can also buy to-go packs of your favorite beverage. Price is what you expect for L.A. BBQ pork rolls 5/10

Croquettes 4/10
Bland croquettes by themselves, but good soft potato texture. Expensive for it's small size. The sauce does not go with these croquettes at all; an off-putting sour flavor.

Yellow Curry (limited special) 2/10
Absolutely awful. There was hardly any curry sauce in it. Maybe a cup. It tasted like water. The rest of my bowl was filled with veggies. The only good thing to say was that the carrots and potatoes were the only things that had any flavor for some reason. I usually finish my meals clean but I couldn't do it this time.

Chicken Skewers 7/10
The most flavorful of all the dishes because of the sauce drizzled on the chicken. Fresh veggies and crisps, but I didn't like how soft the chicken was. Maybe it was undercooked.

Service is very slow so don’t come here if you have plans on seeing a show nearby.

We gave ourselves a little over an hr to eat. We arrived at 624p.

It took maybe 6-8 min for someone to clean a table unless we wanted to sit at the bar, which I didn’t. 632p.

When we were finally seated, we were given our menus to look over. The waitress came back (who appeared to be the only one) and  we told her we’d start w the fried shrimp appetizer. We got waters too but my cup was dirty and something was flowing inside. We asked for another one.

It took about 5 min (636p) for her to come back w a clean one so we were studying the menu meanwhile.

When she finally did come back w my clean up,  we were about to put in our food order but she turned around so quickly that we couldn’t. But she didn’t come back for another 15 min or so !(651p). I actually got up a few times to check for her but didn’t see her or any other waiter around. When I finally spotted her she was on the other side of restaurant busy w other guests.

By this time I’m getting worried bc 1) is our shrimp app still hadn’t arrived and we just put in our food order but we had a show to make at 730 down the street.

We finally got our shrimp (almost 7p).

Luckily our other food arrived faster than our app. But they didn’t come out at the same. So we were sharing the first dish off one plate until the second dish came out.

By the time we got the second dish (710p)  we had less than ten min to eat.

Right when the second dish came out I told the person who brought it out (not the waitress ) to get our waitress. When she arrived I told her we needed to pay at that time so by the time we were done eating we could just leave to make our show.

We ended up inhaling our food and left the restaurant at 720p and walked back down the street to the ahmanson theatre.

As for the food, we got the garlic basil noodle , chicken satay and the shrimp

Everything was so good ! Tho the shrimp was too tough for my liking but flavored really well still.

Also the satay came w rice, crackers and cucumbers but bc we didn’t have time, we only ate the satay and cucumbers.

We had mango chicken, tea leaf salad, beef curry, paratha bread, garlic noodles and a unique dessert. The mango chicken is similar to orange chicken but it actually has big chunks of mango! It was really good. The tea leaf salad is something I’ve never had before. It was good. It includes crunchy things that complement the salad well. The beef curry is pretty good too and not like Thai curry. The garlic noodles were very tasty and the dessert was really good too! The dessert was a bunch of jello type thingies of different colors with some bread pieces and sticky rice in a coconut sauce.  We drank Burmese iced tea as well which is similar to Thai iced tea but tastes more like tea than the Thai version and is far less sweet. Everything here had subtle flavor. The dessert wasn’t overly sweet. If you like food that isn’t overly condimented you’ll love Burmese food. It’s not much like Thai food or Cambodian food. There are some Thai dishes here though. They have a parking lot that is rarely without a spot to park and there’s an underground parking structure as well. I love to eat, I’ve been to many restaurants in LA, all over the spectrum, and I can confidently say that Hummingbird Ceviche House stands out as a gem truly worth visiting. Not only was the food spectacular, but I had the best service I’ve experienced in LA so far

First Impressions~
I’ve seen the muted green building nearly everyday on my drive home through Glendale Boulevard. Stepping inside, you’re immediately immersed in the cozy dining area with bumpin’ music, lights, and a disco ball. I was honestly a little worried at first but my nerves were quickly washed away when our server, Dayana, came around. As first timers, she guided us through the menu and spoke about the food in a way that showed genuine love for the dishes and ingredients.

Food~
We started off with the salmon hand roll, yellowtail ceviche tostada, and the seabass ceviche.
The salmon hand roll came around first. I thought I knew what I expecting, but as soon as I took the first bite and tasted the lemongrass aioli, I knew I was wrong. It was bright, but not overpowering, and I could enjoy the complexities of what I thought was going to be a humble handroll.
We went back and ordered another handroll, this time getting the crab.
I wish I could talk about the other dishes with flowery language but honestly, I was so overjoyed with each one that I couldn’t even think coherent thoughts about what I was tasting.
Despite my blackout, there was one more (humble) stand out — the tostadas themselves. The tostadas must have not been fully corn because they were lighter and airy with a satisfying crunch, like if a corn chip and a rice cracker had a baby. Still, they struck the perfect balance since they were hearty enough to withstand the tigers milk the ceviche was served in as I desperately tried to scoop up every last drop.

From the food, to the vibes, to the service, I am in love with Hummingbird. Will definitely be coming back. Thank you for the wonderful evening!', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'Wow wow wow…

As a Persian, I could definitely taste some authentic flavors that sort of reminded me of my mom’s cooking. I do think the food is geared a bit more towards non-Persians, but that is so okay!

We ordered the ash e jo, the kofteh, and the kotlet sandevich. All were delicious and hit the spot. Definitely recommend the kotlet.

With its relaxed, covered outdoor seating drawing in a wide variety of people—post-workout warriors grabbing a bite, friends meeting for a quick catch-up, and solo diners alike. An option for anyone seeking Persian flavors in a low-key setting.

I started with the mazeh plate, which is essentially a build-your-own bite situation with pickles, feta, herbs, walnuts, and barbari bread alongside two cold dishes. I opted for the wild shallot yogurt and the shirazi salad, a mix of tomato, persian cucumber, onion, mint, and lemon. The bread was the standout here—warmish, well-seasoned and perfect for dipping into anything within reach. The yogurt was ok but didn’t leave much of an impression, and while the shirazi was fresh, it was underwhelming. I also would’ve loved more pickles to round out the plate. The maman’s fried potatoes arrived crispy and golden with a sprinkling of parsley, onion, and sumac, and a side of habanero chatni for some heat. These were seriously addictive.

The turmeric braised jidori chicken was pretty much everything you want in a slow-cooked dish—tender, fall-off-the-bone meat that soaked up all the rich, earthy flavors. Paired with yellow fava bean rice, fried shallots, and house pickles, it was a comforting, aromatic dish. The kofteh tabrizi, a braised beef and rice meatball stuffed with dried stone fruit and walnut, missed the mark for me. While the texture was super soft, the flavor leaned too floral for my liking. It was by far my least favorite dish.

While a few dishes shined brighter than others, the overall quality of the food was solid.
